04008nam a22005535i 9780228016410DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280164107 a10.1515/97802280164102doi  a(DE-B1597)655134  a(OCoLC)1342442766  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1590.A9bJ33 2023 7aLIT0130002bisacsh04a792.012231 aJacobson, Kelsey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReal-ish :bAudiences, Feeling, and the Production of Realness in Contemporary Performance /cKelsey Jacobson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b7 figures, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTable and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tFeeling Real -- t“Everything is True, Some Things are Scripted” -- tTalking to, at, and with Audiences -- t“You Will Long Remember” -- tConstructing Immersive Experiences for “Real” Engagement -- tImmersion and Exertion -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the “post-truth” era, the question of how people perceive things to be real, even when they are not based in fact, preoccupies us. Lessons learned in the theatre – about how emotion and affect produce an experience of realness – are more relevant than ever.Real-ish draws on extensive interviews with audience members about their perceptions of realness in documentary, participatory, historical, and immersive performances. In studying these forms that make up the theatre of the real, Kelsey Jacobson considers how theatrical experiences of realness not only exist as a product of their real-world source material but can also unfurl as real products in their own right. Using the concept of real-ish-ness – which captures the complex feeling that is generated by engaging with elements of reality – the book examines how audiences experience the apparently real within the time and space of a performance, and how it is closely tied to the immediacy and intimacy experienced in relation to others.When feeling – rather than fact –becomes a way of knowing truths about the world, understanding the cultivation and circulation of such feelings of realness is paramount. In exploring this process, Real-ish centres audience voices and, perhaps most importantly, audience feelings during performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmotions. 0aReality. 0aTheater audiencesxPsychology. 0aTheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228016410?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228016410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228016410/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles